00:13:06.100 --> 00:13:11.940
And even just those early stages, it was like, wow, this really makes things possible.

00:13:12.840 --> 00:13:24.000
The challenge is, I mean, this is the big challenge, is people don't discover apps on their mobile devices through progressive web apps, right?

00:13:24.860 --> 00:13:26.360
Hence, your project, right?

00:13:26.810 --> 00:13:32.940
They go to the app store and they click get or buy, and then it shows up on their device, right?

00:13:32.980 --> 00:13:37.640
It's kind of like back to like, well, if you could create a virtual environment, you could run this thing.

00:13:37.820 --> 00:13:43.080
Now, if you can create a progressive web app, I'm a huge fan of them, but it doesn't, my

00:13:43.300 --> 00:13:45.120
fandom doesn't change people's behavior, right?

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:46.220
Sure.

00:13:46.530 --> 00:13:51.000
But there is also, to defend my own project here, I'm a big fan of PyScript.

00:13:51.110 --> 00:13:51.880
I love what they're doing.

00:13:52.320 --> 00:13:54.900
There are limits to what you can do in a progressive web app.

00:13:55.060 --> 00:13:57.560
Those limits are getting extended further and further out.

00:13:57.610 --> 00:14:03.140
But there are things that, if you want to have access to the entire capabilities of your

00:14:03.280 --> 00:14:07.580
device directly at the hardware layer, you can't do that in a progressive web app.

00:14:07.680 --> 00:14:11.120
You can only do it if you're actually writing to the native APIs

00:14:11.310 --> 00:14:12.540
and you've got direct hardware access.

00:14:13.140 --> 00:14:18.620
There are, the web browser sandbox does place some limits

00:14:18.920 --> 00:14:19.680
on what you can do.

00:14:20.160 --> 00:14:21.100
Do those limits matter?

00:14:21.660 --> 00:14:22.980
