And then I'm going to spend a little bit more effort

00:15:11.360 --> 00:15:12.780
and actually make it into a native app

00:15:12.880 --> 00:15:14.260
and get it into the iOS app store.

00:15:14.820 --> 00:15:17.400
You can progress along that chain

00:15:18.640 --> 00:15:19.840
without cutting off any options.

00:15:20.860 --> 00:15:20.940
Yeah.

00:15:21.400 --> 00:15:23.840
Oh, I think your project, the native app side,

00:15:24.600 --> 00:15:25.140
it's critical.

00:15:25.520 --> 00:15:25.840
It's critical.

00:15:26.000 --> 00:15:28.060
I just think there's also a bunch of people out there

00:15:28.200 --> 00:15:29.760
that say, well, I'm going to build a front end,

00:15:29.940 --> 00:15:32.320
interactive front end and have a bunch of Django rest framework

00:15:32.400 --> 00:15:33.340
or something on the back end.

00:15:33.800 --> 00:15:36.240
So I'll use React or I'll use Vue.

00:15:36.460 --> 00:15:38.580
And it's, why isn't the answer Python, right?

00:15:38.700 --> 00:15:40.620
It's really, really could be Python.

00:15:40.960 --> 00:15:43.140
That's kind of, I think, where PyScript has a lot of possibilities.

00:15:43.730 --> 00:15:48.680
And I think that brings us a little bit to one of your keynotes from 2019, where you

00:15:48.830 --> 00:15:50.900
talked about black swan events, right?

00:15:51.600 --> 00:15:51.960
Yes.

00:15:53.260 --> 00:15:56.500
It's a little bit of the same story, but maybe give people a sense of this and we can link

00:15:56.580 --> 00:15:59.140
to this keynote if they want to explore that side of things more.

00:16:00.060 --> 00:16:00.240
Sure.

00:16:00.570 --> 00:16:00.660
Yeah.

00:16:00.760 --> 00:16:05.260
So the idea behind a black swan event was, I'm going to have Nicholas.

00:16:06.260 --> 00:16:07.740
Nassim Talib, I believe it was.

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:08.980
Nassim Talib, that's the one, yep.

00:16:09.370 --> 00:16:09.720
I forget his name.

00:16:10.500 --> 00:16:14.020
But he identified this idea of what's called a black swan event.

00:16:15.940 --> 00:16:18.340
The reason I use it is I'm from Perth and black swans come from Perth.

00:16:18.460 --> 00:16:21.520
So it was an interesting little tie-in for an international keynote.

00:16:22.120 --> 00:16:23.720
You guys actually have black swans all over.

00:16:23.860 --> 00:16:24.120
I got it.

00:16:24.130 --> 00:16:24.460
We have them.

00:16:24.930 --> 00:16:27.500
The state emblem of Western Australia is a black swan.

00:16:27.610 --> 00:16:30.820
Like that is literally on our flag.

00:16:31.660 --> 00:16:39.460
So the theory was that the Dutch bumped into Western Australia accidentally looking for the Spice Islands in the 1600s.

00:16:39.780 --> 00:16:45.060
And at the time they did that, they knew with absolute certainty that all swans were white.

00:16:45.600 --> 00:16:49.640
And then they bumped into Western Australia and they discovered that all the swans here are black.

00:16:51.340 --> 00:16:59.320
The idea behind a black swan event is a thing you don't see coming that completely changes your view of the world.

00:17:00.620 --> 00:17:04.100
And black swan events are the sorts of things that completely change markets.

00:17:04.220 --> 00:17:07.120
We don't know what, you know, if you're not looking,

00:17:07.300 --> 00:17:11.579
if you're not ready for a cataclysmic change in your ecosystem,

00:17:12.140 --> 00:17:14.459
then the change happens and you are left behind.

00:17:15.180 --> 00:17:15.480
Yeah.

00:17:15.819 --> 00:17:20.079
I would say, you know, COVID is a good example of what hit people.

00:17:20.939 --> 00:17:21.680
Another one's AI.

00:17:23.400 --> 00:17:23.500
Yeah.

00:17:23.959 --> 00:17:26.100
AI is still, how is that going to impact?

00:17:26.280 --> 00:17:27.980
It's just a little bit less, little bit less clear.

00:17:28.220 --> 00:17:30.880
And COVID, like we're kind of seeing like the impacts of that,

00:17:31.180 --> 00:17:32.960
whether that's going to have long-term impacts.

00:17:33.180 --> 00:17:35.040
Like some of those things seem to be kind of fading away.

00:17:35.820 --> 00:17:39.080
But the one that I, yeah, well, yeah, mostly.

00:17:39.180 --> 00:17:44.260
I mean, people still get to say, but like the world has shut down.

00:17:45.180 --> 00:17:49.700
And will economies just disappear level of, oh my gosh,

00:17:49.840 --> 00:17:51.580
it's kind of, that's the history I was thinking of.

00:17:51.640 --> 00:17:51.840
Yeah.

00:17:52.500 --> 00:17:56.940
The one that I was highlighting for Python is that Python

00:17:57.040 --> 00:17:57.740
is a programming language.

00:17:58.540 --> 00:18:02.300
but it's a programming language that has historically assumed, well, you're running on a laptop, right?

00:18:02.640 --> 00:18:05.140
Like that's where you run computer code. You always run computer code on a laptop.

00:18:05.720 --> 00:18:11.780
And then iPhones turned up. And now we've got computing in our pocket that is as powerful,

00:18:11.960 --> 00:18:15.040
if not more powerful than the laptops that we had on our desk 10 years ago.

00:18:16.640 --> 00:18:21.040
And Python can't run there, or at least at the time, couldn't really run there.

00:18:21.880 --> 00:18:25.120
So what does that mean for Python? Why am I going to learn Python?

00:18:25.540 --> 00:18:30.240
if the computing ecosystem moves to a world where everybody's using phones and tablets,

00:18:30.920 --> 00:18:35.320
and I can't run Python on a phone or a tablet, why am I going to learn Python?

00:18:35.590 --> 00:18:41.040
Python as an ecosystem has an existential risk there because of this black swan of a change in

00:18:41.050 --> 00:18:47.580
the way people do computing. And at the time I gave that keynote, what I was essentially saying

00:18:47.590 --> 00:18:52.799
is, okay, as an ecosystem, we need to take a long, hard look at ourselves. It's impossible to know

00:18:52.800 --> 00:18:54.660
what the black swan events are going to be,

00:18:55.320 --> 00:18:57.460
but we can look at where the ecosystem is now.

00:18:57.530 --> 00:18:59.240
We can look at the trends of things that are happening

00:18:59.310 --> 00:19:03.180
and we can work out institutionally what are our risks,

00:19:03.380 --> 00:19:08.680
like what would need to change to make Python a dead ecosystem.

00:19:09.920 --> 00:19:12.500
And the obvious one, the one that I was really pushing

00:19:12.590 --> 00:19:16.340
at that time, one of which is platforms that we need to support,

00:19:16.450 --> 00:19:20.020
and the second is how do we support this software going forward?

00:19:20.200 --> 00:19:25.480
How do we actually guarantee that this community-driven project continues to be maintained?

00:19:25.820 --> 00:19:29.060
Because if we don't have maintainers, then the code doesn't get written.

00:19:30.300 --> 00:19:30.540
So, yeah.

00:19:31.299 --> 00:19:31.700
Yeah.

00:19:32.860 --> 00:19:32.960
Excellent.

00:19:33.140 --> 00:19:34.420
I recommend people check it out.

00:19:34.580 --> 00:19:35.020
It's on YouTube.

00:19:35.240 --> 00:19:36.460
I will link to it.

00:19:38.679 --> 00:19:39.080
Scary.

00:19:39.120 --> 00:19:40.000
That was five years ago.

00:19:40.660 --> 00:19:41.060
I know.

00:19:41.260 --> 00:19:42.940
I feel like that was pretty recent.

00:19:43.180 --> 00:19:43.480
But no.

00:19:44.500 --> 00:19:44.860
No.

00:19:44.980 --> 00:19:47.840
That was the last one before COVID, by the way, bringing it full circle.

00:19:48.720 --> 00:19:54.660
Tommy out there asked in the audience, is in the iOS Pythonistas app, I had some really good simple use cases in the past.

00:19:54.960 --> 00:20:02.680
The GUI layer, a bit of a hassle, but like the library modules, also could not call some not yet exposed APIs.

00:20:03.240 --> 00:20:08.140
I guess as we get into this, maybe think just people probably know about the Pythonista app.

00:20:09.080 --> 00:20:10.140
I don't know.

00:20:10.460 --> 00:20:10.580
Yeah.

00:20:11.760 --> 00:20:11.840
Yeah.

00:20:11.960 --> 00:20:12.780
It was around.

00:20:13.540 --> 00:20:14.620
And it's not the same idea.

00:20:14.840 --> 00:20:16.180
It's not what you guys are trying to do.

00:20:17.020 --> 00:20:17.660
Yes and no.

00:20:17.920 --> 00:20:19.820
Because I actually worked on Pythonista.

00:20:20.270 --> 00:20:22.200
The reason that Pythonista supports Python 3,

00:20:22.630 --> 00:20:24.720
I was contracted to do the Python 3 port.

00:20:24.770 --> 00:20:28.400
So the core of that library is essentially the thing that Bware was doing.

00:20:28.470 --> 00:20:31.520
And the reason it was able to move to Python 3 was because of the work that I was doing.

00:20:32.740 --> 00:20:37.160
It is, yeah, it is very much the sort of the Pythonista as an idea is kind of,

00:20:37.640 --> 00:20:40.700
what if idle, but on a phone?

00:20:41.120 --> 00:20:45.420
Like here is a development environment where you can write Python code,

00:20:45.600 --> 00:20:49.500
you have some access to some libraries and some GUI libraries.

00:20:50.500 --> 00:20:53.700
So you can put a button up, but you're not writing,

00:20:54.000 --> 00:20:56.540
you're not using Pythonista to write an app.

00:20:57.020 --> 00:21:02.579
You're using it to put an interface into a running Pythonista sheet,

00:21:03.360 --> 00:21:04.320
you know, working environment.

00:21:05.380 --> 00:21:07.580
It is absolutely a way to write Python.

00:21:07.640 --> 00:21:11.340
It is a way to have Python running on your phone.

00:21:11.880 --> 00:21:14.220
But it is not something that's going to push something

00:21:14.240 --> 00:21:15.240
to the iOS app store.

00:21:15.460 --> 00:21:18.100
so that random other person can buy your app.

00:21:18.520 --> 00:21:21.620
You know, to me, it feels a little bit like shortcuts on iOS

00:21:22.720 --> 00:21:25.280
in that you could kind of put together some behaviors,

00:21:25.680 --> 00:21:27.160
but you would never try to make an app.

00:21:28.919 --> 00:21:30.480
Yeah, that's not too far from it.

00:21:30.820 --> 00:21:32.800
Except that it's all inside the sandbox.

00:21:33.600 --> 00:21:34.660
Yeah, and you could do real Python,

00:21:34.860 --> 00:21:36.200
which is way better than shortcuts.

00:21:36.680 --> 00:21:39.180
But the kind of the type of thing you accomplish,

00:21:39.300 --> 00:21:41.980
it feels a little bit like I can go find this thing and run it

00:21:41.980 --> 00:21:43.520
and it'll do something for me, which is cool.

00:21:43.720 --> 00:21:48.580
but it's not going to be the new Airbnb implementation.

00:21:49.840 --> 00:21:50.240
No, exactly.

00:21:50.540 --> 00:21:54.760
And even, I guess, Beware as a project isn't...

00:21:55.360 --> 00:22:01.080
The intention is not that it would be the next Airbnb as a final product.

00:22:01.300 --> 00:22:04.940
It might, however, be the mock-up of the demo app

00:22:04.960 --> 00:22:08.900
that you take to your initial seed funding round to prove,

00:22:09.240 --> 00:22:11.080
here is the idea we've got.

00:22:11.280 --> 00:22:14.500
We've proved it out with some people, just like a small little sample trial, whatever.

00:22:15.180 --> 00:22:24.700
Now give us the money to go and actually hire a team of iOS developers and a team of Android developers to build an absolutely kick-ass, optimized native application of every platform.

00:22:25.260 --> 00:22:25.620
Yeah.

00:22:27.400 --> 00:22:30.840
Maybe a little bit like Playgrounds as well, perhaps, in that regard.

00:22:31.500 --> 00:22:32.980
Yeah, a little bit, I guess, like Playgrounds, yeah.

00:22:33.780 --> 00:22:35.060
Yeah, also a different focus.

00:22:35.240 --> 00:22:39.600
But another comment, maybe as we dive into this, Joe out there asks, hey, great project.

00:22:39.890 --> 00:22:41.480
How would you sell this to us?

00:22:42.100 --> 00:22:44.600
And that there's a few other frameworks like WXPython, Kivy.

00:22:46.080 --> 00:22:47.720
WXPython also renders data of GUIs.

00:22:50.120 --> 00:22:51.260
How would I sell it?

00:22:51.500 --> 00:22:53.920
Okay, says he, pulling out the sales sheet.

00:22:54.720 --> 00:22:55.940
Let me get my pushback.

00:22:55.990 --> 00:22:56.320
Hold on.

00:22:57.660 --> 00:22:59.460
So there's essentially two questions there.

00:22:59.580 --> 00:23:02.340
One is WXPython and one is Kivy.

00:23:03.920 --> 00:23:07.720
The Kivy is a, sort of the two different reasons.

00:23:08.100 --> 00:23:09.900
Kivy does work on iOS and Android

00:23:10.280 --> 00:23:11.440
and also on the desktop platforms.

00:23:11.920 --> 00:23:14.640
Kivy is taking a very, very distinctly different approach

00:23:14.880 --> 00:23:15.880
to user interface design.

00:23:16.820 --> 00:23:18.980
So Kivy can run on all of those platforms,

00:23:19.580 --> 00:23:21.340
but the user interface that it puts up

00:23:21.720 --> 00:23:22.780
is a Kivy user interface.

00:23:23.160 --> 00:23:24.320
It always looks like Kivy.

00:23:24.320 --> 00:23:25.760
And it's like, if you build a macOS app,

00:23:26.020 --> 00:23:28.560
it will look the same on Windows,

00:23:28.760 --> 00:23:29.880
it'll look the same on GTK,

00:23:30.160 --> 00:23:31.140
and it will look the same, you know,

00:23:31.420 --> 00:23:32.460
size of window notwithstanding,

00:23:32.480 --> 00:23:34.320
it will look the same on iOS and Android.

00:23:35.140 --> 00:23:38.220
That is a completely viable way to build apps.

00:23:38.780 --> 00:23:41.480
It is not a native user interface.

00:23:42.640 --> 00:23:44.680
The reason, and one of the major reasons

00:23:45.020 --> 00:23:47.800
that I dislike that as an approach,

00:23:48.220 --> 00:23:50.520
I'm not in any way saying that Kibbe is a bad project.

00:23:50.700 --> 00:23:52.480
It is a different way to build user interfaces

00:23:52.700 --> 00:23:53.980
and I prefer a different approach,

00:23:54.440 --> 00:23:56.620
which is to say an actual native button.

00:23:56.840 --> 00:23:59.480
So on macOS, it looks like a macOS app.

00:23:59.600 --> 00:24:01.760
On iOS, it looks like an iOS app.

00:24:01.820 --> 00:24:03.740
On Windows, it looks like a Windows app.

00:24:05.260 --> 00:24:11.580
The downside is that if you need to take screenshots, you've got to have an iOS screenshot and a macOS screenshot and a Windows screenshot.

00:24:13.140 --> 00:24:16.460
The benefit is consistency with the rest of the platform.

00:24:17.440 --> 00:24:26.120
And that might seem like a totally cosmetic thing, but one, consistency between applications is a mode of user interface discovery.

00:24:26.160 --> 00:24:29.800
because if people know this is how a button works on MacOS,

00:24:30.140 --> 00:24:32.060
they know how your platform does it as well,

00:24:32.060 --> 00:24:32.960
how your app does it as well,

00:24:33.450 --> 00:24:35.780
rather than having to discover how you have decided

00:24:35.880 --> 00:24:38.560
to implement menus or buttons or anything else.

00:24:39.060 --> 00:24:40.880
Yeah, one of the really things that stands out,

00:24:40.880 --> 00:24:42.460
I think, super stark a lot of times

00:24:42.550 --> 00:24:44.280
is the file open save dialogues.

00:24:44.620 --> 00:24:45.500
Yes, yes.

00:24:45.540 --> 00:24:49.540
It's like, whoa, this is clearly just alien versus...

00:24:49.560 --> 00:24:50.800
Yeah, and a lot of cases,

00:24:51.260 --> 00:24:53.839
they are missing the one thing on my platform

00:24:53.860 --> 00:24:56.220
that makes file dialogues actually useful

00:24:56.680 --> 00:24:59.780
because I can do this thing that I can't do in your dialogue

00:25:00.160 --> 00:25:01.220
because you've had to build it from scratch.

00:25:01.360 --> 00:25:02.620
And speaking of building from scratch,

00:25:02.680 --> 00:25:04.800
the other big benefit of a native GUI

00:25:05.160 --> 00:25:08.020
is that you get all of the platform's native affordances.

00:25:08.760 --> 00:25:10.380
One of the most surprising things,

00:25:10.440 --> 00:25:11.800
it wasn't necessarily surprising

00:25:12.080 --> 00:25:13.540
because I understood why I was doing it,

00:25:13.660 --> 00:25:15.100
but things that might be surprising to people

00:25:15.140 --> 00:25:16.600
who haven't followed along GUI development,

00:25:17.500 --> 00:25:19.840
we have received an inordinate number

00:25:20.340 --> 00:25:22.479
of very, very enthusiastic comments

00:25:22.500 --> 00:25:25.700
from blind people writing iOS apps.

00:25:26.510 --> 00:25:28.660
Because an iOS app built with Beware

00:25:29.540 --> 00:25:32.240
fits in directly with screen readers

00:25:32.520 --> 00:25:35.560
because it is using the platform's native accessibility.

00:25:36.360 --> 00:25:38.800
Kivy has not built explicitly

00:25:39.450 --> 00:25:41.080
native screen reader support into their widgets.

00:25:41.310 --> 00:25:42.400
To the best of my knowledge,

00:25:42.620 --> 00:25:44.120
or at least all the reports that I'm getting

00:25:44.120 --> 00:25:45.280
are saying that it's not there

00:25:45.640 --> 00:25:47.620
because you have to build it from scratch

00:25:48.160 --> 00:25:50.480
on every platform and they haven't done that.

00:25:51.380 --> 00:25:52.200
It's a lot of work.

00:25:52.360 --> 00:25:54.400
I'm not underselling how big of a project it is,

00:25:54.540 --> 00:25:56.580
but Beware got it for free

00:25:57.200 --> 00:25:58.760
because we are using native widgets.

00:25:59.260 --> 00:26:01.040
And that's not an insignificant consideration.

00:26:02.620 --> 00:26:03.760
So that's Kivy.

00:26:03.820 --> 00:26:04.060
Oh, sorry.

00:26:04.600 --> 00:26:05.300
No, no, please go ahead.

00:26:05.980 --> 00:26:07.500
No, I was going to say, that's the Kivy.

00:26:07.820 --> 00:26:09.860
So that's the not native user interface,

00:26:10.120 --> 00:26:10.860
but looks the same everywhere

00:26:11.340 --> 00:26:13.860
versus Beware's using native widgets everywhere.

00:26:14.220 --> 00:26:15.200
The other argument is, okay,

00:26:15.220 --> 00:26:16.520
but why don't you use WX Windows?

00:26:16.900 --> 00:26:18.000
The reason we don't use WX Windows

00:26:18.100 --> 00:26:20.779
is WX Windows doesn't run on iOS or Android

00:26:20.800 --> 00:26:23.080
and trying to make it run on iOS and Android.

00:26:23.350 --> 00:26:25.160
Like I did look into it and it was a little bit crunchy.

00:26:26.520 --> 00:26:29.240
Qt apparently works on iOS now.

00:26:29.310 --> 00:26:30.680
It didn't when I started the project,

00:26:32.040 --> 00:26:34.180
but they very much don't want you to write Python.

00:26:34.270 --> 00:26:35.940
And one of the things that Beware is trying to push

00:26:35.980 --> 00:26:37.760
and Toga as a GUI platform is trying to push

00:26:37.850 --> 00:26:39.640
is you're writing Python code.

00:26:39.760 --> 00:26:40.560
It looks like Python.

00:26:40.670 --> 00:26:41.740
It tastes like Python.

00:26:42.180 --> 00:26:43.860
If you don't want to write Python, that's fine.

00:26:44.060 --> 00:26:45.480
There are plenty of GUI toolkits out there

00:26:45.490 --> 00:26:47.140
that don't require you to write Python.

00:26:47.490 --> 00:26:50.360
But Toga is a Python first GUI toolkit.

00:26:50.480 --> 00:27:01.120
And it looks like, tastes like Python, we support, we use, actively use in APIs, iterators and generators and asyncio syntax and context managers.

00:27:01.600 --> 00:27:14.020
Things that WX Windows as a light wrapper around a C++ framework doesn't really expose because they are limited by what C++ looks like when you program it.

00:27:14.920 --> 00:27:19.180
And to a certain extent, you also get that to a certain extent in QT as well or in QT.

00:27:19.440 --> 00:27:43.200
Yeah, they're both wrappers. Yeah. Yeah. Interesting. So let's talk about some of the peps that make this possible, right? Yeah, there's, there's the foundational basically adding platforms as a intentionally supported platform to the CPython whole process, right?

00:27:43.260 --> 00:27:48.140
The core developers working on it from the builds and the deployments and all those kinds of things.

00:27:48.210 --> 00:27:52.840
And so you've got a couple of peps where you're the author of them, which is awesome.

00:27:53.120 --> 00:27:54.960
I'm strictly the author of one.

00:27:55.060 --> 00:27:56.480
Malcolm Smith was the author of the Android one.

00:27:56.640 --> 00:27:56.980
Oh, okay.

