What role they have and their status is final.

00:28:12.460 --> 00:28:14.160
Oh, that's good.

00:28:15.000 --> 00:28:19.580
So yeah, the PEP was essentially formalizing the things

00:28:19.780 --> 00:28:23.200
that Malcolm and I have been maintaining independently,

00:28:23.740 --> 00:28:26.140
both of us at the time for like about eight, nine years.

00:28:27.960 --> 00:28:28.600
We had patches.

00:28:29.040 --> 00:28:30.880
Like I was maintaining a set of patches

00:28:31.180 --> 00:28:32.880
to make CPython run on iOS.

00:28:33.060 --> 00:28:34.760
And I was manually maintaining all those patches.

00:28:34.940 --> 00:28:37.020
And every time a new Python release would come out,

00:28:37.140 --> 00:28:39.680
I'd have to go and sit down and spend, you know,

00:28:39.840 --> 00:28:40.960
a couple of months trying to work out,

00:28:41.020 --> 00:28:42.360
okay, what have they changed this time?

00:28:42.840 --> 00:28:44.920
and, you know, getting all of those,

00:28:45.780 --> 00:28:48.380
updating all of the PR or all of the code

00:28:48.380 --> 00:28:50.600
to make it work on a new version of Python.

00:28:51.960 --> 00:28:58.480
In the 3.13 timeframe, so it's, what, September of 2023,

00:28:59.260 --> 00:29:05.460
I went along to the CPython core team summit in the US.

00:29:05.940 --> 00:29:08.260
Sorry, it was in Bono.

00:29:09.920 --> 00:29:14.520
And basically with the intention of, I want to form, I want to upstream all these patches.

00:29:14.680 --> 00:29:15.300
We've got these patches.

00:29:15.480 --> 00:29:16.040
They're not huge.

00:29:16.140 --> 00:29:17.420
They're big, but they're not huge.

00:29:17.760 --> 00:29:18.740
I'd like to formalize that.

00:29:18.960 --> 00:29:20.760
And so the outcome of that was what we need is a PEP.

00:29:20.880 --> 00:29:25.060
We need a formal description of what it is you're going to do, why it's going to change,

00:29:25.240 --> 00:29:31.700
what impact that has on the rest of the ecosystem for you to do that, and to formalize a couple

00:29:31.880 --> 00:29:37.560
of the little details that need to be formally specified in order for the rest of the ecosystem

00:29:37.620 --> 00:29:38.400
to play nice with this.

00:29:38.640 --> 00:29:42.700
Little details like, what does sys.platform return on an iOS machine?

00:29:43.180 --> 00:29:46.500
Like, it's a really minor detail, but it's a question you've got to answer.

00:29:46.970 --> 00:29:48.080
And it's like it's an answer to even Apple.

00:29:48.080 --> 00:29:48.760
Darwin is probably wrong.

00:29:49.800 --> 00:29:50.520
Well, yeah, that's the thing.

00:29:50.610 --> 00:29:53.300
Like, it's Darwin on macOS for some historical reasons.

00:29:53.490 --> 00:29:55.520
But like, even on iOS, should it be iOS?

00:29:55.880 --> 00:29:57.600
Should it be iOS capitalized?

00:29:57.980 --> 00:29:59.200
Should it be iPhone?

00:29:59.650 --> 00:30:00.640
Should it be iPhone OS?

00:30:00.780 --> 00:30:02.820
Should it be iPhone OS or iPhone simulator?

00:30:03.180 --> 00:30:06.760
All of these are answers that Apple itself uses at various points in their API.

00:30:06.840 --> 00:30:08.880
but you need to have a formal spec.

00:30:09.380 --> 00:30:10.620
Well, an iPad is iPad iOS.

00:30:10.750 --> 00:30:11.440
Is that a different answer?

00:30:12.000 --> 00:30:12.740
And so on.

00:30:13.680 --> 00:30:15.960
And then the one that really matters for that is nailing down

00:30:16.220 --> 00:30:21.540
what is the platform tag that will be used for packaging purposes?

00:30:21.720 --> 00:30:25.740
So when a wheel, a binary wheel, eventually lands on PyPI,

00:30:26.880 --> 00:30:27.520
what's the tag?

00:30:27.650 --> 00:30:28.980
Like what is it?

00:30:29.340 --> 00:30:33.500
For macOS, it's a macOS X underscore 11 underscore ARM64.

00:30:34.470 --> 00:30:34.600
Okay?

00:30:35.000 --> 00:30:35.720
What is it for iPhone?

00:30:36.480 --> 00:30:37.260
Yeah, maybe we could elaborate.

00:30:37.500 --> 00:30:40.400
Maybe you could elaborate just a little bit on what that even means, right?

00:30:40.580 --> 00:30:43.240
Because before Wheels, things were different.

00:30:43.280 --> 00:30:44.000
You would download it.

00:30:44.000 --> 00:30:44.560
You would build it.

00:30:44.620 --> 00:30:46.480
You'd have to have Fortran or some random thing.

00:30:47.060 --> 00:30:51.420
Wheels solved that, but that then created a combinatorial explosion of binary assets, right?

00:30:51.980 --> 00:30:52.480
Why does that matter?

00:30:53.420 --> 00:30:54.240
Why does that matter?

00:30:54.280 --> 00:31:05.840
So the major change with Wheels is that it moved from a world where installing a Python package required you to execute code at time of installation.

00:31:07.680 --> 00:31:17.520
And that's not a good idea from a security perspective, because you then need to audit all of the code that's going to execute when you install the package.

00:31:18.100 --> 00:31:25.060
And you can't find anything out about the package without running that code or at least auditing the code that's going to run.

00:31:25.880 --> 00:31:35.600
Wheels provide you to say, okay, this is a wheel is basically just a zip file with a bunch of known metadata that describes exactly what is in here.

00:31:36.040 --> 00:31:41.800
But part of that specification is also a binary specification that says what version of CPython is it compatible with?

00:31:42.060 --> 00:31:44.320
What version of the operating system is it compatible with?

00:31:44.720 --> 00:31:46.900
What CPU architecture is it compatible with?

00:31:47.260 --> 00:31:58.840
So that if I look at a wheel that is labeled, for example, macOS 11.0 ARM64, I know that this will run on macOS 11 with an ARM64 CPU.

00:31:59.520 --> 00:32:01.700
There are any number of these tags available.

00:32:01.840 --> 00:32:07.640
And there's differences like the Universal 2, which will support both x86 and ARM.

00:32:08.100 --> 00:32:26.740
And on Linux, there's a thing called a mini Linux wheel, which is a specification for specifically what API guarantees does this Linux platform guarantee in terms of what is available in the CPython, in terms of the C library, the GNU C library, et cetera, et cetera.

00:32:26.900 --> 00:32:32.480
You have to be able to specify that so that I know when I get this wheel, I know where it will work and how it will work.

00:32:32.530 --> 00:32:36.440
And for the point of view of pip, pip knowing which version should I download?

00:32:37.080 --> 00:32:39.700
I've got an app here that I'm running on my macOS machine.

00:32:40.140 --> 00:32:41.420
Which wheel should I download?

00:32:41.880 --> 00:32:44.820
Go and grab one and resolve it and find out, solve that question.

00:32:45.680 --> 00:32:45.820
Yeah.

00:32:46.140 --> 00:32:50.020
So without knowing that answer, you don't know how to install wheels, basically.

00:32:51.900 --> 00:32:52.040
Correct.

00:32:52.120 --> 00:33:07.380
Yeah, you've got the part of the wheel specification is which if the wheel contains all the precompiled components in order for it to have precompiled components, there's like there's an API or an ABI specification there of exactly what's what symbols am I going to be able to link against?

00:33:07.410 --> 00:33:08.700
What can I assume exists?

00:33:09.260 --> 00:33:09.340
Yeah.

00:33:09.520 --> 00:33:11.040
And that will just run on my machine.

00:33:12.140 --> 00:33:12.260
Yeah.

00:33:12.980 --> 00:33:13.960
What's going to happen, right?

00:33:14.080 --> 00:33:15.440
Is it even a pie from architecture?

00:33:15.580 --> 00:33:22.280
And we have a similar thing with Python standalone builds that is now part of Astral, which is really great.

00:33:22.310 --> 00:33:26.460
We can just grab the Python we need because we know the platform tags and all that kind of stuff.

00:33:28.440 --> 00:33:31.120
Any difference about the Android one?

00:33:31.230 --> 00:33:34.420
I mean, you obviously need one for each platform, I suppose.

00:33:35.440 --> 00:33:35.940
We do, yeah.

00:33:36.550 --> 00:33:41.100
And there will be at some point in the hopefully not too distant future, there will be one for Inscripten as well.

00:33:41.300 --> 00:33:43.320
just formalizing in script and support,

00:33:43.670 --> 00:33:47.680
which is the Pyodide slash PyScript in the browser version.

00:33:49.020 --> 00:33:51.340
Yeah, you need to have one for every platform.

00:33:51.530 --> 00:33:56.400
I guess the one notable difference between iOS and Android as a PEP

00:33:56.980 --> 00:34:03.200
is that in theory, CPython 12 could compile on Android.

00:34:03.360 --> 00:34:05.840
There were some patches which had been applied

00:34:05.910 --> 00:34:07.698
without going through the formal PEP process

00:34:07.720 --> 00:34:12.679
on the basis of, well, it doesn't cost us anything to add this code in.

00:34:12.800 --> 00:34:15.280
We're not guaranteeing it's going to work, but it's not breaking anything,

00:34:15.389 --> 00:34:16.419
so we might as well have it there.

00:34:16.980 --> 00:34:24.419
And so there's one, like, the process of formalizing it did change one notable thing,

00:34:24.980 --> 00:34:29.460
which is that previously, if you were able to get CPlatform to compile on Android,

00:34:29.530 --> 00:34:32.780
and it was possible and realistically it needed some patches, but it could be done,

00:34:33.700 --> 00:34:39.220
sys.platform would return Linux because technically it is,

00:34:40.360 --> 00:34:43.100
but not in a way that's even remotely helpful to anyone.

00:34:44.540 --> 00:34:47.040
And so one of the things that the tech specified,

00:34:47.260 --> 00:34:50.620
yes, it is a Linux kernel, but Linux doesn't help you there

00:34:50.720 --> 00:34:54.620
because nothing about an Android machine actually behaves like Linux

00:34:55.399 --> 00:34:57.700
once you're past the kernel level.

00:34:58.500 --> 00:35:00.320
The rest of the thing is what you actually care about,

00:35:00.840 --> 00:35:03.240
and the rest of the libraries you can guarantee is what you care about.

00:35:03.660 --> 00:35:08.280
And so one of the things that the PEP had to specify was, okay,

00:35:08.800 --> 00:35:11.500
we are changing what sys.platform means on Android

00:35:11.970 --> 00:35:14.600
because you need to be able to differentiate.

00:35:14.870 --> 00:35:18.280
I am on an Android machine, not just a desktop Linux box.

00:35:19.380 --> 00:35:21.500
And so, yeah, so that was one notable change.

00:35:21.680 --> 00:35:24.100
It was in that PEP that wasn't in the iOS one.

00:35:24.340 --> 00:35:24.740
Interesting.

00:35:26.280 --> 00:35:27.960
You mentioned mscripten.

00:35:28.580 --> 00:35:29.660
What an interesting project.

00:35:29.970 --> 00:35:30.480
Yeah, tell.

00:35:31.860 --> 00:35:35.060
It almost looks like it's about AI because it's LLVM,

00:35:35.500 --> 00:35:36.500
but it has nothing to do with that.

00:35:36.590 --> 00:35:36.880
Yeah, yes.

00:35:37.280 --> 00:35:39.620
It's a different set of LLs altogether.

00:35:40.640 --> 00:35:40.780
Yeah.

00:35:41.560 --> 00:35:46.980
So Inscription is kind of the tail end,

00:35:46.990 --> 00:35:51.420
the current manifestation of a long series of developments

00:35:51.680 --> 00:35:53.580
that started like 15 years ago.

00:35:54.140 --> 00:35:58.878
Someone worked out that modern web browsers

00:35:59.020 --> 00:36:04.740
have spent so much time optimizing the JavaScript compilers

00:36:05.200 --> 00:36:08.320
that there are certain JavaScript constructs

00:36:08.740 --> 00:36:11.440
that map almost one-to-one to machine code.

00:36:11.690 --> 00:36:15.020
Like you can say, okay, add these two integers in JavaScript

00:36:15.770 --> 00:36:17.320
or these two numbers in JavaScript,

00:36:17.560 --> 00:36:19.600
that if you know the numbers are integers,

00:36:20.680 --> 00:36:26.920
will map through the JavaScript jits that are running.

00:36:26.980 --> 00:36:30.320
It will map to a literal, you know, ad instruction.

00:36:30.540 --> 00:36:32.940
Like two registers coming together sort of thing.

00:36:32.940 --> 00:36:34.040
Yeah, two registers coming together.

00:36:34.640 --> 00:36:41.860
And so if you restrict yourself to handwriting just that subset of JavaScript,

00:36:42.920 --> 00:36:46.920
you can essentially write Assembler in JavaScript.

00:36:48.280 --> 00:36:53.620
Now, in practice, nobody can actually do that because it's just way too constraining to know that you can only,

00:36:53.720 --> 00:36:59.120
You actually have to put the brackets around the outside of here or else the JIT won't optimize it in just the right way.

00:36:59.760 --> 00:37:00.980
But that's what compilers are for.

00:37:01.420 --> 00:37:06.940
Compilers are really good at taking a set of arbitrary input and following a set of arbitrary rules to produce a consistent set of output.

00:37:07.460 --> 00:37:17.920
And so this thing called ASM.js was born, which is essentially an input format that could be compiled to a JIT-able version of JavaScript that would run as a native platform.

00:37:18.580 --> 00:37:23.260
And then from that, you can then get to WASM, which is WebAssembly, which is a formal text

00:37:23.420 --> 00:37:26.160
specification of the sort of things that ASN.js was working on.

00:37:26.530 --> 00:37:31.540
And then Inscripten is a compiler tool chain that plugs into LLVM.

00:37:31.550 --> 00:37:38.940
So if you've used a compiler like Clang, it is essentially a wrapper around a set of compiler

00:37:39.120 --> 00:37:41.460
building tools that produces output.

00:37:42.000 --> 00:37:47.060
So you are used to calling GCC or Clang on a CPO program.

00:37:47.900 --> 00:37:56.820
Clang calls into your C program, compiles it into an LLVM format, and LLVM converts it into actual runnable executables.

00:37:57.500 --> 00:38:12.540
And so it's an LLVM plugin that instead of spitting out macOS-compatible binary executable assembly, it spits out JavaScript-optimized code that can run in the browser.

00:38:13.420 --> 00:38:15.200
That's all very much high level.

00:38:15.320 --> 00:38:17.540
There's a lot of very, very complicated details that go on in the internals.

00:38:17.720 --> 00:38:22.340
But the end point is that Enscripten lets you take any arbitrary C code

00:38:22.760 --> 00:38:25.640
and compile it to JavaScript that will run in a browser

00:38:25.920 --> 00:38:28.640
at nearish native speed.

00:38:31.040 --> 00:38:33.240
The good news is that CPython is written in C.

00:38:33.540 --> 00:38:37.560
And so you can compile CPython into a JavaScript version

00:38:37.820 --> 00:38:40.800
or into this JavaScript subset, and it will run in the browser.

00:38:41.160 --> 00:38:43.000
There's a bunch of other stuff you need to do as well,

00:38:43.120 --> 00:38:44.900
and Enscripten is providing a bunch of other things,

00:38:45.080 --> 00:38:47.760
like guaranteeing a bunch of unique system calls are available.

00:38:48.520 --> 00:38:49.920
But broadly, that's the idea here.

00:38:49.920 --> 00:38:52.780
So you can take any C code and have it run in the browser.

00:38:53.420 --> 00:38:55.800
And at that point, Python is just C code.

00:38:56.240 --> 00:38:58.140
So all of a sudden, yeah.

00:38:58.350 --> 00:39:00.780
But the best news is because the browser is everywhere,

00:39:01.170 --> 00:39:03.080
because JavaScript interpreters are everywhere,

00:39:04.340 --> 00:39:06.560
you've now got cross-platform binaries.

00:39:06.960 --> 00:39:09.340
You've got a format that you can compile to once,

00:39:09.690 --> 00:39:12.860
and it will run pretty much everywhere because, like,

00:39:13.720 --> 00:39:16.940
existentially, every platform that matters has a web browser now,

00:39:16.990 --> 00:39:18.520
which means it's got the ability to run JavaScript.

00:39:19.100 --> 00:39:22.900
And so JavaScript becomes this cross-platform format

00:39:23.390 --> 00:39:25.540
without ever actually being JavaScript the language.

00:39:25.760 --> 00:39:27.800
It's just kind of exploiting some weird quirks

00:39:27.800 --> 00:39:29.200
of the way JavaScript works as a language.

00:39:30.120 --> 00:39:32.640
It's like saying you never write assembly,

00:39:32.920 --> 00:39:35.060
but you kind of still do machine instructions,

00:39:35.300 --> 00:39:35.780
but you never-

00:39:35.780 --> 00:39:37.080
But you're always writing assembly.

00:39:37.220 --> 00:39:38.200
Yeah, exactly.

00:39:38.200 --> 00:39:42.340
There's a really, if you go back, oh gosh, 12, 13 years,

00:39:42.560 --> 00:39:46.680
Gary Bernhardt gave a talk at PyCon called The Birth and Death of JavaScript.

00:39:47.500 --> 00:39:48.160
So good.

00:39:48.440 --> 00:39:49.240
It was so good.

00:39:50.040 --> 00:39:50.800
It is hilarious.

00:39:51.600 --> 00:39:54.740
At the time, it was just straight up, oh, this is a funny gag,

00:39:55.260 --> 00:39:59.920
except that he has accurately predicted the next 15 years of software development

00:40:00.340 --> 00:40:01.940
in terms of the way everything has gone.

00:40:02.240 --> 00:40:05.560
And I've never spoken to Gary about it, so I don't know, like,

00:40:06.300 --> 00:40:11.240
how much of this was just for the giggles and how much of it was accurately,

00:40:11.400 --> 00:40:12.740
Like this is where things are going.

00:40:14.340 --> 00:40:15.380
But as it turns out-

00:40:15.380 --> 00:40:19.240
- It was really, really entertaining

00:40:19.240 --> 00:40:22.200
and really technically well presented

00:40:22.200 --> 00:40:23.320
and predicted like you said, yeah.

00:40:24.370 --> 00:40:24.740
- Yes.

00:40:24.740 --> 00:40:26.560
- And for people who are not familiar with this stuff,

00:40:26.560 --> 00:40:27.700
like one of the examples he showed,

00:40:27.700 --> 00:40:28.740
I don't know if he came up with it

00:40:28.740 --> 00:40:31.900
or he was just quoting and showing it off,

00:40:32.680 --> 00:40:35.160
but somebody took Mozilla Firefox, I think,

00:40:35.160 --> 00:40:36.720
and compiled that into Emscriptum,

00:40:36.720 --> 00:40:38.620
was running inside of Chrome,

00:40:38.620 --> 00:40:40.400
but then inside the embedded Firefox was running,

00:40:40.900 --> 00:40:44.260
like Doom compile, Doom inscription, or some crazy 3D.

00:40:44.480 --> 00:40:45.180
I mean, it was wild.

00:40:46.500 --> 00:40:46.580
Yeah.

00:40:46.780 --> 00:40:51.160
Like, the list of things you can do once you've got the ability

00:40:51.190 --> 00:40:58.720
to compile C is truly phenomenal, purely because the C compiler tool chain

00:40:58.940 --> 00:41:04.480
for all of the flaws of C as a language, C's lingua franca.

00:41:04.600 --> 00:41:06.300
C is where everything is done.

00:41:06.940 --> 00:41:07.740
It's in-depth, yeah.

00:41:07.900 --> 00:41:11.040
we're now kind of removing like the whole thing with LLVM is essentially we're

00:41:11.160 --> 00:41:14.440
removing C from the front end, letting you put any language you want on the front.

00:41:15.040 --> 00:41:17.880
But now we can use the same tool chain to target any platform we want.

00:41:17.880 --> 00:41:22.180
And so you've, you've, you've divorced the language, the specific language from

00:41:22.480 --> 00:41:25.680
the, the tool chain that is producing a platform specific binaries.

00:41:26.660 --> 00:41:26.980
Nice.

00:41:28.040 --> 00:41:30.460
All right, let's talk about some of the projects and get some updates on them.

00:41:30.850 --> 00:41:35.238
I know it's been a while and you know, you've got a lot of support from

00:41:35.260 --> 00:41:36.860
Anaconda, which, you know, thank you again.

00:41:37.840 --> 00:41:38.420
Yes, absolutely.

00:41:38.780 --> 00:41:39.400
That's awesome.

00:41:40.700 --> 00:41:42.780
So we'll maybe touch on some of the high-level

00:41:43.100 --> 00:41:44.240
or most important ones.

00:41:44.540 --> 00:41:44.680
Toga?

00:41:45.660 --> 00:41:48.500
Yeah, so Toga, the cross-platform GUI toolkit.

00:41:48.690 --> 00:41:53.640
So this is the analog of a Kivi or a QT or a WX Windows.

00:41:54.260 --> 00:41:55.820
It's the API that lets you say,

00:41:55.910 --> 00:41:57.300
I want a window that has a button.

00:41:57.470 --> 00:42:00.800
And when I press the button, the light goes off,

00:42:00.860 --> 00:42:02.140
whatever you want it to do.

00:42:02.240 --> 00:42:04.040
Put this text in the label or whatever.

00:42:04.360 --> 00:42:05.120
Exactly, exactly.

00:42:06.170 --> 00:42:11.380
So it is cross-platform, pure Python, runs cross-platform.

00:42:12.400 --> 00:42:14.820
And by cross-platform, I mean all the desktop platforms,

00:42:14.940 --> 00:42:18.160
so Windows, macOS, Linux with GTK.

00:42:18.920 --> 00:42:20.080
It runs as a web.

00:42:20.600 --> 00:42:22.020
There's a web backend and a textual backend.

00:42:22.140 --> 00:42:24.220
Both of those are very early prototypes, but I can't,

00:42:24.230 --> 00:42:26.600
like there are demos I can do that demonstrate that it works.

00:42:27.580 --> 00:42:28.780
And also iOS and Android.

00:42:29.860 --> 00:42:32.398
So essentially anywhere that you might want plausibly

00:42:32.420 --> 00:42:35.040
to have a user interface, I can give you a user interface

00:42:35.480 --> 00:42:36.260
purely written in Python.

00:42:37.680 --> 00:42:41.020
We also cover a bunch of hardware services as well.

00:42:41.090 --> 00:42:44.220
So, for example, you can, using a pure Python interface,

00:42:44.720 --> 00:42:45.960
get a GPS read.

00:42:45.990 --> 00:42:47.360
You can work out where you are at a GPS,

00:42:47.800 --> 00:42:48.740
and we have a native WAC widget.

00:42:48.920 --> 00:42:51.440
So you can say, get a GPS read and put it by center of the map

00:42:51.490 --> 00:42:52.680
of where I am currently standing.

00:42:53.030 --> 00:42:55.920
